{{for|the census-designated place|Anchor Point, Alaska}}
In [[audio recording|audio]] and [[Sound recording and reproduction|recording]], what is known colloquially as an '''''anchor point''''' is a center position in a [[stereo mix]] reserved for only three or four important [[track (audio)|tracks]].<ref name="Hodgson">Hodgson, Jay (2010). ''Understanding Records'', p. 165. {{ISBN|978-1-4411-5607-5}}.</ref> Most modern [[pop music|pop]] productions are anchored by lead ([[lead vocals|vocals]] and [[solo (music)|soloing]] instruments), [[bass guitar|bass]], [[kick drum]], and [[snare drum]].<ref name="Hodgson"/> These are usually within a few degrees of center (horizontal) and front (proximity or depth) in the [[audio mixing (recorded music)|mix]].<ref name="Hodgson"/> Exceptions include early stereo recordings using "stereo-switching" (a three-way switch allowing only left output, right output, or both) rather than [[pan pot]]s<ref>Hodgson (2010), p. 161.</ref>) such as the [[The Beatles|Beatles]]'s "[[Strawberry Fields Forever]]" and [[Jimi Hendrix]]'s "[[Purple Haze]]".<ref name="Hodgson"/> Examples of tracks using anchor points include [[The Breeders]]'s "[[Cannonball (The Breeders song)|Cannonball]]", [[The Cure]]'s "[[Catch (The Cure song)|Catch]]", [[Lady Gaga]]'s "[[Just Dance (song)|Just Dance]]", [[Lily Allen]]'s "[[The Fear (Lily Allen song)|The Fear]]", [[Radiohead]]'s "[[OK Computer|Airbag]]", [[Squarepusher]]'s "[[Just a Souvenir|Star Time 2]]", [[Stone Roses]]'s "[[One Love (The Stone Roses song)|One Love]]", and [[Weezer]]'s "[[My Name Is Jonas]]".<ref>Hodgson (2010), p. 165–166.</ref>

