'''''Canaan Hymns''''' or '''''Songs of Canaan''''' ({{lang-zh|c=迦南诗选|p=Jiānán Shīxuǎn}}{{sfn|Starr|2016|p=28}}<ref name="Zhou2011">{{cite book|last=Zhou|first=Kate|title=China's Long March to Freedom: Grassroots Modernization|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CvzebFwWRAcC&pg=PA141|year=2011|publisher=Transaction Publishers|location=New Brunswick|isbn=978-1-4128-1520-8|page=141}}</ref>{{sfn|Strandenæs|2008|p=156}}) is a collection of [[China|Chinese]] hymns composed by [[Lu Xiaomin|Lü Xiaomin]], a Christian convert peasant woman with no musical education. She proved to be a prolific song writer after starting to write hymns in 1990. {{As of|2016|02}}, she has written 1,682 Canaan hymns. Xiaomin's [[Christian theology|theologically]] background is in [[Pentecostalism]] and the [[Local churches (affiliation)|local churches movement]], and the hymns reflect themes of [[Christology]], [[Pneumatology (Christianity)|pneumatology]] and [[Christian eschatology|eschatology]] against the backdrop of Chinese political realities.

Canaan hymns are one of the most successful underground Christian publication in China. They are used by many Protestant churches in the country. Both [[Chinese house churches]] and churches of the [[Three-Self Patriotic Movement]] use them, despite the latter having criticized the hymns through its official channels. The [[Chinese government]] has targeted censorship efforts on the distributors of the hymnal. [[Overseas Chinese]] communities and [[Taiwan]]ese churches use the hymnal, too.

Even people with little education can learn the hymns, which are short and musically simple, usually rhymed, and resemble [[Chinese folk songs]]. This has contributed to their popularity. The can also be sung without instruments. Their Chinese elements and [[Confucian]] undertones make them more acceptable than foreign hymnals to Chinese worshipers. There is a strong emphasis on the communal aspects of the Christian church. Some hymns are patriotic.

==History==
[[Lu Xiaomin|Lü Xiaomin]] ({{lang-zh|c=吕小敏|p=Lǔ Xiǎo Mǐn}};{{sfn|Starr|2016|p=28}}{{sfn|Strandenæs|2008|p=157}} also known as Sister Ruth{{sfn|Aikman|2012|p=108}}) was born in 1970 to a family of peasants belonging to the [[Hui people|Hui]] minority.{{sfn|Starr|2016|p=356}}{{sfn|Aikman|2012|p=108}} She grew up in [[Fangcheng County|Fangcheng]], [[Nanyang, Henan|Nanyang]], [[Henan Province]].<ref name="Hawn2015">{{cite book|last=Hawn|first=C. Michael|editor-last=Brunn|editor-first=Stanley D.|title=The Changing World Religion Map: Sacred Places, Identities, Practices and Politics|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CGh-BgAAQBAJ&pg=PA2665|date=2015|publisher=Springer|location=Dordrecht|isbn=978-94-017-9376-6|page=2665|chapter=Landscapes and Soudscapes: How Place Shapes Christian Congregational Song}}</ref>

Xiaomin dropped out of education after elementary school because of her failing health. Because the Hui are China's largest [[Muslim]] community, she was initially unfamiliar with Christianity.{{sfn|Aikman|2012|p=108}} Her aunt, who had converted to Christianity, introduced her to the faith.{{sfn|Aikman|2012|pp=108–109}} After praying, her health condition, [[sinusitis]] and a stomach disease, were gone.<ref name="Wang2016"/> Xiaomin joined a house church in 1989, at the age of 19,{{sfn|Aikman|2012|p=109}} taking the [[christian name]] "Sister Ruth".{{sfn|Aikman|2012|p=108}} Her spiritual roots are in [[Pentecostalism]] and [[Local churches (affiliation)|the local churches movement]].{{sfn|Starr|2016|p=355}}

In 1990, she started composing hymns.{{sfn|Starr|2016|p=356}}{{sfn|The Canaan Hymns|2003|loc=14:00}} The first hymn came to her mind one night after church service when she could not sleep.{{sfn|Aikman|2012|p=109}} According to Xiaomin: "The Holy Spirit touched me the moment I consecrated myself to God. That's when I sang my first hymn."{{sfn|The Canaan Hymns|2003|loc=14:00}} Shy as she was, she only sang the song to a girl in her home village. The girl relayed the hymn to her parents, Christians who attributed Xiaomin's sudden musical abilities to the work of the [[Holy Spirit]]. By the time that word about Xiaomin's song had reached a fellow Christian with a tape recorder, she had already written 23 hymns. All of them were taped and marked down in [[Chinese musical notation]]. Soon all of the local congregations were using the hymnal and traveling evangelists took it all over China.{{sfn|Aikman|2012|p=109}}

Xiaomin continued to compose new hymns, one every two or three days.{{sfn|Aikman|2012|p=110}} During the next decade of her life, she would write some 700 of them while evangelizing in the countryside of Henan.{{sfn|Starr|2016|pp=355–356}} During this period, she was detained at least twice for her religious activities.{{sfn|Starr|2016|p=356}} The first arrest took place in September 1992 in Fangcheng after she had written 50 songs.{{sfn|Aikman|2012|p=110}}{{sfn|The Canaan Hymns|2003|loc=31:00}} During her 67-day detention, she composed 14 additional hymns and her seven non-Christian cellmates had become converted to Christianity.{{sfn|Aikman|2012|p=110}} The other arrest came after a 1998 re-interpretation of the illegal publications clause of the [[Constitution of China]].<ref name="Zhou2011"/> By the year 2000, the hymnal consisted of some 720 songs.{{sfn|Aikman|2012|p=110}}

==Use==
{{As of|2016|02}}, there are 1,682 Canaan hymns.<ref name="Wang2016">{{Cite web | title = 'I Compose Hymns By Prayers', Xiao Min, Composer of Canaan Hymns Shared Her Story | last = Wang| first = Ruth | work = China Christian Daily | date = 6 February 2016 | accessdate = 13 February 2017 | url = http://chinachristiandaily.com/2016-02-06/church/-i-compose-hymns-by-prayers---xiao-min--composer-of-canaan-hymns-shared-her-story-_534.html}}</ref> The songs are extremely popular all over China.{{sfn|Starr|2016|p=355}}{{sfn|Aikman|2012|p=112}} They are used by many [[Protestant]] Chinese churches, both in the People's Republic of China and in [[Taiwan]] and have been published in both countries. [[Overseas Chinese]] communities use them as well.{{sfn|Strandenæs|2008|p=156}}

Canaan hymns are one of the most successful underground Christian publication in China.<ref name="Zhou2011"/> They are predominantly used in the [[House church (China)|Chinese house churches]], where they are considered its "official hymnal". They also see use in the government-sanctioned [[Three-Self Patriotic Movement]] churches.{{sfn|Neeley|2016|p=591}} Through its official channels, the Three-Self Patriotic Movement has criticized the hymns. A 1999 issue of its ''[[Tian Feng (magazine)|Tian Feng]]'' magazine scrutinized the hymn 195, "Lord, Have Mercy on China, Hold Back Your Anger", in particular for questioning the Movement's view of Christianity in service of Chinese socialism.{{sfn|Aikman|2012|p=110}} The government has targeted publishers and distributors of the hymnal.<ref name="Zhou2011"/>

Neither Xiaomin nor anyone in her family has any formal musical training.{{sfn|Aikman|2012|p=109}} She does not know how to write either Western or Chinese musical notation.<ref>{{Cite web | title = You Are the Light of the World, Song for Preachers, Created by China's Songbird, Lv [sic] Xiao Min | last = Wang| first = Ruth | work = China Christian Daily | date = 15 December 2015 | accessdate = 13 February 2017 | url = http://chinachristiandaily.com/2015-12-15/ministry/you-are-the-light-of-the-world--song-for-preachers--created-by-china-s-songbird--lv-xiao-min_349.html}}</ref> Initially, her hymns spread mainly orally, but they have since begun to be transcribed by others.<ref name="Hawn2015"/> Orchestral adaptations of the hymns have made Xiamin famous overseas as well.{{sfn|Starr|2016|p=356}} Her life story and the hymns are inseparable in publicity, reflecting a holiness [[Christian theology|theology]] on part of the movement.{{sfn|Starr|2016|p=355}} Described as "profoundly modest" despite her fame in China, Xiaomin spends much time traveling around the country.{{sfn|Aikman|2012|p=111}} Her music is publicized by [[Chinese American]] backers in particular.{{sfn|Starr|2016|p=355}}

The 2012 Chinese film ''[[Back to 1942]]'' featured the Canaan hymn "The River of Life" as its theme song. The hymn "I Love My Home" has also appeared on [[China Central Television]],{{sfn|The Canaan Hymns|2003|loc=44:00}}{{sfn|Golf|2013|p=164}} sung by a Christian family,{{sfn|The Canaan Hymns|2003|loc=44:00}} despite the channel's reputation as propaganda of the officially atheist state.{{sfn|Golf|2013|pp=28, 163}}

Many Chinese regard the Canaan hymns a gift from God.<ref name="Hawn2015"/> Chinese Christians have attributed miraculous healings to those singing the hymns.{{sfn|Aikman|2012|p=110}}

==Musical and theological features==
{{Quote box|quote=<poem>My Lord leads me into His gates
Our loving words flow endlessly
Our love is as strong as death
Many waters cannot quench it
My Lord is radiant
Outstanding among all others
I am His and He is mine
We will never part
He takes me to the fields
He takes me to the vineyards
He feeds His flock among the lilies
I am with Him forever</poem>|source="The Lord and I" (Canaan hymn 85){{sfn|The Canaan Hymns|2003|loc=39:00}}}}
The Canaan hymns are short,{{sfn|Strandenæs|2008|p=156}} [[pentatonic]] and resemble [[Chinese folk music|Chinese folk songs]].{{sfn|Neeley|2016|pp=591–592}} Many, but not all, are rhymed. Few have verses or refrains. There are many allusions to nature and the weather.{{sfn|Starr|2016|p=357}} They are "genuinely inculturated hymns, with a folk lilt, Chinese harmonics, and an imagery that blends rural China with biblical themes".{{sfn|Starr|2016|p=356}} The spontaneity of the hymns reflect the process that Xiaomin uses to compose her hymns: she develops songs based on [[Bible verses]] that come to her mind while praying, as a plea to a local need or as thanks.{{sfn|Starr|2016|p=357}} Conceiving a new hymn can take as little as five to ten minutes.<ref name="Hawn2015"/> The songs are simple, "a few lines of doxology or lament";{{sfn|Starr|2016|p=357}} the figures of speech used are everyday and rural.{{sfn|Starr|2016|p=358}} The songs are easier to learn than those featured in the ''[[Chinese New Hymnal]]'', the official hymnal of the state-controlled [[China Christian Council]]. Even uneducated and illiterate people can grasp the Canaan hymns, which has contributed to their popularity.{{sfn|Strandenæs|2008|p=156}} They can be sung without instrumentation,{{sfn|The Canaan Hymns|2003|loc=4:00}} and are sung in church, at home gatherings, and when alone.{{sfn|Strandenæs|2008|p=156}}

The songs are [[Christology|Christologically]] and [[Pneumatology (Christianity)|pneumatologically]] focused, even if most of the Biblical references are to the [[Old Testament]], especially the [[Book of Psalms]].{{sfn|Starr|2016|p=358}} The lyrics of the hymns are theologically mindful of a tension between China's political realities and aspirations of Chinese Christians. These thoughts are reflected on the [[Second Coming]] of [[Jesus]] and there is a strong [[Christian eschatology|eschatological]] current.{{sfn|Starr|2016|p=359}} Early hymns in particular focused on the theme of overcoming hardships.{{sfn|Starr|2016|p=357}} The hymnody reflects a kind of "enduring acceptance of state persecution."{{sfn|Starr|2016|p=355}}

Their Chinese elements and [[Confucian]] undertones make them more acceptable than foreign hymnals to Chinese audiences.{{sfn|Neeley|2016|pp=591–592}} There is a strong emphasis on the communal aspects of the Christian church. Some hymns, such as "Chinese Heart" and "The Chinese shall Rise", are markedly patriotic.{{sfn|Strandenæs|2008|pp=157–158}} Canaan hymns also exhibit the "Three self principles" that are central to Chinese Protestantism, "self-governance, self-reliance, and self-propagation", often supplemented with a fourth one: "ingeniousness".{{sfn|Strandenæs|2008|p=158}} These aspects make Canaan hymns compatible with government-sanctioned Christianity.{{sfn|Starr|2016|p=358}} Some have the air of [[work song]]s,{{sfn|Starr|2016|pp=357–358}} and even contain mimicry of [[Cultural Revolution]] era propaganda songs.{{sfn|Starr|2016|p=359}}

