'''The Setters''' was a collaborative musical project between [[rock-n-roll]] songwriters [[Walter Salas-Humara]] of [[the Silos]], [[Alejandro Escovedo]] of [[True Believers (band)|True Believers]], and [[Michael Hall (musician)|Michael Hall]] of the [[Wild Seeds]]. The band originated when Hall told a music festival he wanted to play at that he was in a band with Salas-Humara and Escovedo. Hall came up with the band name "The Setters" off the top of his head when the festival organizers asked him what the band's name was. Hall then called up Salas-Humara to ask him to perform with him at the festival, and Salas-Humara agreed.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://nodepression.com/article/walter-salas-humara-man-behind-silos-turns-his-radar-gun | title=Walter Salas-Humara - The man behind the Silos turns on his Radar gun | work=[[No Depression (magazine)|No Depression]] | date=31 October 1996 | accessdate=22 May 2017 | author=Fox, Randy}}</ref> They released a single, self-titled album in 1993 on the German [[Blue Million Miles]] record label, and which was released the following year in the United States on [[Watermelon Records]].<ref name=tp>{{cite web | url=http://www.trouserpress.com/entry.php?a=silos | title=The Silos | work=[[Trouser Press]] | accessdate=22 May 2017 | author=Schinder, Scott}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1994-05-13/entertainment/9405110665_1_salas-humara-alejandro-escovedo-true-believers | title=The Setters, The Silos, True Believers | work=[[Orlando Sentinel]] | date=13 May 1994 | accessdate=22 May 2017 | author=Gettelman, Parry}}</ref> The album was produced by [[Gurf Morlix]], and featured performances by [[accordion]]ist [[Lisa Mednick]] and bassist [[Scott Garber]] ([[Giant Sand]]).<ref name=tp/> The tracks on the album are all new recordings of songs originally written by Salas-Humara, Escovedo, or Hall.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/110214744/ | title=The Setters Review | work=[[Louisville Courier-Journal]] | date=28 May 1994 | accessdate=22 May 2017}}</ref> Brian Beatty gave the album 3 stars out of 5, writing, "Though there's no arguing with the quality of the songs here, most of them have appeared on albums much better than this one. Purchase those albums first."<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/setters-mw0000113211 | title=The Setters Review | work=[[AllMusic]] | accessdate=22 May 2017 | author=Beatty, Brian}}</ref>

